Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and finely chop the @shallot{1}(finely chopped). Halve the @lemon{1}. Drain and rinse the @capers{1%ounce}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium heat. Add the shallot. Cook, tossing, for ~{2-3%minutes}, until softened. Add the @Israeli couscous{3/4%cup}, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, 2 cups water, and a large pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, cover, and reduce to a low simmer for ~{10-12%minutes}, until tender.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add the @spinach{5%ounce} and toss until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and @pepper{}, and cover to keep warm.

Season the @rockfish{12%ounce} on all sides with salt and pepper. Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Once very hot, add the fish. Cook ~{2-3%minutes} per side, until lightly golden brown and almost opaque in the center.

== Lemon Caper Sauce ==

Make the sauce: Turn off the heat, then add the @thyme{1/4%ounce} sprigs and @butter{2%tablespoon} to the pan. Once melted, spoon over the fish. Add the capers and the juice of half a lemon, and cook until warmed through. Season the sauce with salt and pepper. Discard the thyme.

> Piccata is a simple yet elegant cooking style where meat or fish is sautéed and served with a lemon, caper, herb, and butter sauce. Although piccata is traditionally associated with chicken or veal, rockfish is a perfect choice because it's mild and flaky but doesn't fall apart while cooking.

== To Serve ==

Plate: Serve the rockfish piccata on a bed of Israeli couscous and sautéed spinach. Drizzle with the lemon caper sauce. Enjoy!